The paper leverages geo-located information obtained from Twitter to understand transnational migration patterns between two border cities. This involves the use of social networks and technology-based empirical perspective, which suggests that the paper could belong to the sub-categories of Social and Information Sciences (cs.SI), Social and Information Networks (cs.SOC), Cybersecurity and Privacy (cs.CYBER), Computer Engineering (cs.CE), and Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC).
